    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if the concrete is mostly just handling the squishing part, what's actually happening inside the slab when it's under a heavy load? like, how does the tension actually get transferred to the steel? i dont really get how they work together on an internal level.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When a heavy load is applied to the slab, it creates internal stresses, and these stresses manifest as both compression and tension across the concrete. The concrete, being the strong compressive element, takes the brunt of the squeezing forces. The steel rebar, which is strategically placed in the areas predicted to experience the highest *tensile* stress—usually near the bottom of beams or slabs—is what gets pulled taut. This pulling action is the tension, and the steel resists it, preventing the concrete from fracturing, which is the very definition of how they work together.",
      "source": "target",
